modules.name: AWS.DynamoDB
modules.comments:
Amazon DynamoDB is a fast, highly scalable, highly available, cost-effective non-relational database service.

Amazon DynamoDB removes traditional scalability limitations on data storage while maintaining low latency and predictable performance.

declarations.comments:
Retrieves the attributes for multiple items from multiple tables using their primary keys.

The maximum number of item attributes that can be retrieved for a single operation is 100. Also, the number of items retrieved is constrained by a 1 MB the size limit. If the response size limit is exceeded or a partial result is returned due to an internal processing failure, Amazon DynamoDB returns an UnprocessedKeys value so you can retry the operation starting with the next item to get.

Amazon DynamoDB automatically adjusts the number of items returned per page to enforce this limit. For example, even if you ask to retrieve 100 items, but each individual item is 50k in size, the system returns 20 items and an appropriate UnprocessedKeys value so you can get the next page of results. If necessary, your application needs its own logic to assemble the pages of results into one set.
declarations.title: batchGetItem

declarations.comments:
Allows to execute a batch of Put and/or Delete Requests for many tables in a single call. A total of 25 requests are allowed.

There are no transaction guarantees provided by this API. It does not allow conditional puts nor does it support return values.
declarations.title: batchWriteItem

declarations.comments:
Adds a new table to your account.

The table name must be unique among those associated with the AWS Account issuing the request, and the AWS Region that receives the request (e.g. us-east-1).

The CreateTable operation triggers an asynchronous workflow to begin creating the table. Amazon DynamoDB immediately returns the state of the table (CREATING) until the table is in the ACTIVE state. Once the table is in the ACTIVE state, you can perform data plane operations.
declarations.title: createTable

declarations.comments:
Deletes a single item in a table by primary key.

You can perform a conditional delete operation that deletes the item if it exists, or if it has an expected attribute value.
declarations.title: deleteItem

declarations.comments:
Deletes a table and all of its items.

If the table is in the ACTIVE state, you can delete it. If a table is in CREATING or UPDATING states then Amazon DynamoDB returns a ResourceInUseException. If the specified table does not exist, Amazon DynamoDB returns a ResourceNotFoundException.
declarations.title: deleteTable

declarations.comments:
Retrieves information about the table, including the current status of the table, the primary key schema and when the table was created.

If the table does not exist, Amazon DynamoDB returns a ResourceNotFoundException.
declarations.title: describeTable

declarations.comments:
Retrieves a set of Attributes for an item that matches the primary key.

The GetItem operation provides an eventually-consistent read by default. If eventually-consistent reads are not acceptable for your application, use ConsistentRead. Although this operation might take longer than a standard read, it always returns the last updated value.
declarations.title: getItem

declarations.comments: Retrieves a paginated list of table names created by the AWS Account of the caller in the AWS Region (e.g. us-east-1).
declarations.title: listTables

declarations.comments:
Creates a new item, or replaces an old item with a new item (including all the attributes).

If an item already exists in the specified table with the same primary key, the new item completely replaces the existing item. You can perform a conditional put (insert a new item if one with the specified primary key doesn't exist), or replace an existing item if it has certain attribute values.
declarations.title: putItem

declarations.comments:
Gets the values of one or more items and its attributes by primary key (composite primary key, only).

Narrow the scope of the query using comparison operators on the RangeKeyValue of the composite key. Use the ScanIndexForward parameter to get results in forward or reverse order by range key.
declarations.title: query

declarations.comments:
Retrieves one or more items and its attributes by performing a full scan of a table.

Provide a ScanFilter to get more specific results.
declarations.title: scan

declarations.comments:
Edits an existing item's attributes.

You can perform a conditional update (insert a new attribute name-value pair if it doesn't exist, or replace an existing name-value pair if it has certain expected attribute values).
declarations.title: updateItem

declarations.comments:
Updates the provisioned throughput for the given table.

Setting the throughput for a table helps you manage performance and is part of the Provisioned Throughput feature of Amazon DynamoDB.
declarations.title: updateTable

declarations.comments: The type of action for an item update operation. Only use the add action for numbers or sets; the specified value is added to the existing value. If a set of values is specified, the values are added to the existing set. Adds the specified attribute. If the attribute exists, it is replaced by the new value. If no value is specified, this removes the attribute and its value. If a set of values is specified, then the values in the specified set are removed from the old set.
declarations.title: AttributeAction

declarations.comments: List of Attribute names. If attribute names are not specified then all attributes will be returned. If some attributes are not found, they will not appear in the result.
declarations.title: AttributeNameList

declarations.comments: Map of attribute name to the new value and action for the update. The attribute names specify the attributes to modify, and cannot contain any primary key attributes.
declarations.title: AttributeUpdates

declarations.comments: AttributeValue can be String, Number, Binary, StringSet, NumberSet, BinarySet.
declarations.title: AttributeValue

declarations.comments: A list of attribute values to be used with a comparison operator for a scan or query operation. For comparisons that require more than one value, such as a BETWEEN comparison, the AttributeValueList contains two attribute values and the comparison operator.
declarations.title: AttributeValueList

declarations.comments: Specifies the attribute to update and how to perform the update. Possible values: PUT (default), ADD or DELETE.
declarations.title: AttributeValueUpdate

declarations.comments: A map of the table name and corresponding items to get by primary key. While requesting items, each table name can be invoked only once per operation.
declarations.title: BatchGetRequestMap

declarations.comments: Table names and the respective item attributes from the tables.
declarations.title: BatchGetResponseMap

declarations.comments: The item attributes from a response in a specific table, along with the read resources consumed on the table during the request.
declarations.title: BatchResponse

declarations.comments: A container for BatchWriteItem response
declarations.title: BatchWriteItemOutput

declarations.comments:
A map of table name to list-of-write-requests.

Key: The table name corresponding to the list of requests

Value: Essentially a list of request items. Each request item could contain either a PutRequest or DeleteRequest. Never both.
declarations.title: BatchWriteItemRequestMap

declarations.comments:
A comparison operator is an enumeration of several operations:

  • EQ for equal.
  • NE for not equal.
  • IN checks for exact matches.
  • LE for less than or equal to.
  • LT for less than.
  • GE for greater than or equal to.
  • GT for greater than.
  • BETWEEN for between.
  • NOT_NULL for exists.
  • NULL for not exists.
  • CONTAINS for substring or value in a set.
  • NOT_CONTAINS for absence of a substring or absence of a value in a set.
  • BEGINS_WITH for a substring prefix.

Scan operations support all available comparison operators.

Query operations support a subset of the available comparison operators: EQ, LE, LT, GE, GT, BETWEEN, and BEGINS_WITH.
declarations.title: ComparisonOperator

declarations.comments: This exception is thrown when an expected value does not match what was found in the system.
declarations.title: ConditionalCheckFailedException

declarations.comments: If set to true, then a consistent read is issued. Otherwise eventually-consistent is used.
declarations.title: ConsistentRead

declarations.comments: The number of Capacity Units of the provisioned throughput of the table consumed during the operation. GetItem, BatchGetItem, BatchWriteItem, Query, and Scan operations consume ReadCapacityUnits, while PutItem, UpdateItem, and DeleteItem operations consume WriteCapacityUnits.
declarations.title: ConsumedCapacityUnits

declarations.comments: A container for a Delete BatchWrite request
declarations.title: DeleteRequest

declarations.comments: Designates an attribute for a conditional modification. The Expected parameter allows you to provide an attribute name, and whether or not Amazon DynamoDB should check to see if the attribute has a particular value before modifying it.
declarations.title: ExpectedAttributeMap

declarations.comments: Allows you to provide an attribute name, and whether or not Amazon DynamoDB should check to see if the attribute value already exists; or if the attribute value exists and has a particular value before changing it.
declarations.title: ExpectedAttributeValue

declarations.comments: This exception is thrown when the service has a problem when trying to process the request.
declarations.title: InternalServerError

declarations.comments: The primary key that uniquely identifies each item in a table. A primary key can be a one attribute (hash) primary key or a two attribute (hash-and-range) primary key.
declarations.title: Key

declarations.comments: The KeySchema identifies the primary key as a one attribute primary key (hash) or a composite two attribute (hash-and-range) primary key. Single attribute primary keys have one index value: a HashKeyElement. A composite hash-and-range primary key contains two attribute values: a HashKeyElement and a RangeKeyElement.
declarations.title: KeySchema

declarations.comments: KeySchemaElement is the primary key (hash or hash-and-range) structure for the table.
declarations.title: KeySchemaElement

declarations.comments: This exception is thrown when the subscriber exceeded the limits on the number of objects or operations.
declarations.title: LimitExceededException

declarations.comments: A number of maximum table names to return.
declarations.title: ListTablesInputLimit

declarations.comments: Provisioned throughput reserves the required read and write resources for your table in terms of ReadCapacityUnits and WriteCapacityUnits. Values for provisioned throughput depend upon your expected read/write rates, item size, and consistency. Provide the expected number of read and write operations, assuming an item size of 1k and strictly consistent reads. For 2k item size, double the value. For 3k, triple the value, etc. Eventually-consistent reads consume half the resources of strictly consistent reads.
declarations.title: ProvisionedThroughput

declarations.comments: This exception is thrown when the level of provisioned throughput defined for the table is exceeded.
declarations.title: ProvisionedThroughputExceededException

declarations.comments: A map of the attributes for the item, and must include the primary key values that define the item. Other attribute name-value pairs can be provided for the item.
declarations.title: PutItemInputAttributeMap

declarations.comments: A container for a Put BatchWrite request
declarations.title: PutRequest

declarations.comments: This exception is thrown when the resource which is being attempted to be changed is in use.
declarations.title: ResourceInUseException

declarations.comments: This exception is thrown when the resource which is being attempted to be changed is in use.
declarations.title: ResourceNotFoundException

declarations.comments:
Use this parameter if you want to get the attribute name-value pairs before or after they are modified. For PUT operations, the possible parameter values are NONE (default) or ALL_OLD. For update operations, the possible parameter values are NONE (default) or ALL_OLD, UPDATED_OLD, ALL_NEW or UPDATED_NEW.

  • NONE: Nothing is returned.
  • ALL_OLD: Returns the attributes of the item as they were before the operation.
  • UPDATED_OLD: Returns the values of the updated attributes, only, as they were before the operation.
  • ALL_NEW: Returns all the attributes and their new values after the operation.
  • UPDATED_NEW: Returns the values of the updated attributes, only, as they are after the operation.
declarations.title: ReturnValue

declarations.comments: This structure is a Union of PutRequest and DeleteRequest. It can contain exactly one of PutRequest or DeleteRequest. Never Both. This is enforced in the code.
declarations.title: WriteRequest
